{"cursor":"3208","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn physics a 'conserved current' is a current, j^\\mu , that\nsatisfies the continuity equation \\partial_\\mu j^\\mu=0 . The\ncontinuity equation represents a conservation law, hence the name.\n\nIndeed, integrating the continuity equation over a volume V ,\nlarge enough to have no net currents through its surface, leads to the\nconservation law\n: {\\partial\\over\\partial t}Q=0\\;,\nwhere Q=\\int_V j^0dV is the conserved quantity.\n\nIn gauge theories the gauge fields couple to conserved currents. For example,\nthe electromagnetic field couples to the conserved electric current.\n","linknr":121,"url":"Conserved_current","recorded":1362583888,"links":12,"instances":["waves"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Electromagnetism","Theoretical physics","Partial differential equations","Conservation laws","Symmetry"],"headings":["Conserved quantities and symmetries","Conserved currents in electromagnetism"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/6/d/56dc363686f42e4477150035497975f7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/5/1/b519199f69cfde1ebe8b9a582487f894.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/6/0/360f9681bc42f0c54848ba5ef0ae1fa9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/6/2/8623841053905ff9ce965e369777dc1a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/a/5/fa51da272998ef8891db042f65aedb70.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/7/f/f7f177957cf064a93e9811df8fe65ed1.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["phase","waves"]],"members":["phase"],"related":["Physics","Continuity_equation","Gauge_theory","Electromagnetic_field","Charge_conservation","Canonical_conjugate","Cont